				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Hi friends.<BR>
I am posting this reply to clear some missunderstanding that some people might have undertook, wholly understandable if you're unfamiliar with dragon raids (tho you will get there soon I hope ;)<BR>
When it comes to lore No-Drop items needed for quests (especially the White Dragon Scale needed for Bards &amp; the Frost/Burnt Book needed for Paladins) it's either merited or claimed by the raid organizer if they need it..<BR>
Whenever I'm invited to join a Vox/Nagafen raid, a common question to ask is &quot;Is the paladin book reserved?&quot; if it is (&amp; it always is when the raid organizer is a Paladin), well, I go volunteer my effort to help the Paladin who went through the hassle of organizing the whole raid to get his epic piece, if it is not, I go wishing i might win the roll on it..<BR>
I do not see where the &quot;greedy&quot; word fits in here, if the item I'm looking for is No-Drop needed to get another item that is also No-Drop, &amp; when I organized the raid, gathered people, bought expensive spell components, organized group, pathing &amp; strategy just for the sole reason of getting this piece (&amp; wont roll for other items).<BR>
If an individual wishes to join the raid  &amp; doesnt like the rules the raid leader put, then he will just : 1- Dont join, &amp; wish to join another raid soon enough with the rules he approves or 2- Get his own raid organized &amp; goes through the pain of gathering people &amp; such to help him get the item he/she needs. (well guess what?.. I'm doing number 2:)<BR>
If when in a raid a CoF drops, &amp; the raid organizer sais only WARRIORS roll on it, then only warriors roll, if you're a rogue &amp; dont like it, you can moan all you want about it but you still wont get the CoF on this raid, since it's his/her raid to boot.<BR>
I offered my rules, put them straight &amp; forward on the table for people to read &amp; understand. Approving?.. You're welcome to join. Dont?.. well, too bad, you just missed a spot on a nice dragon raid that maybe would have given you a chance at an awesome roll. Big deal.<BR>
I personally cant picture a level 45 paladin who has never been on a dragon raid before wishing to join a raid I organized, &amp; expecting to have the same go as me on the book I organized the raid just to get. That would seem ridiculous. It's only fair. You don't like it, do your own raid (that's what I did anyway) People earn their epics, &amp; that wont just be by joining a raid &amp; wishing to get lucky on a roll (well, not for all your Epic components anyway, you will have to do some work to get at least some components)..;)<BR>
I know that once you get to the level where you can go on raids you will understand that point friend(s), I wish you all good luck.<BR>
&amp; for the people who are on the list or wish to join, please make sure to be at the permafrost zone at due time with /LFG on. It's either Vox is going to kneel, or the zone crashes from overcrowdness..LOL<BR>
<BR>
Rewarding hunting everyone<BR>
<BR>
Summmoneaa
